(1) Weehawken Street, west side, north from but not including Christopher Street (where it commences), to and including West 10th Street (where it terminates), showing an old 2½-story house in a state of collapse, bearing No. 391 West Street (all houses here shown bear West Street numbers). On the extreme left appears a portion of the West Side Vehicular Express Highway. May 15, 1937. P. L. Sperr.

(2) The same, a better view of the buildings which surplanted the Weehawken Market about 1830. About 1936. Gift of Dr. Michael Wishengrad, A.R.P.S.

Weehawken Street, west side, between Christopher and West 10th Street, showing the rear of the building bearing No. 393 West Street. This is popularly supposed to be the oldest structure in Manhattan. It rests on the site of the Weehawken Market, and which in turn succeeded to a portion of the old State Prison of 1797-1829. For further information, see, the New York Times of, Sunday, August 22, 1937. also : N.Y. Eve Post June 15, 1930.
About 1939
